reviews.review_text:
Trust a Gem 
Listeners of audience recordings can always trust a Gem. James Young is a taper supreme and he used his Neumann 89's. Very sweet, yet very dynamic. Plus Evans and Waddell are expert at transfers. Their philosophy is to do as much or as little as possible to present the most accurate reproduction of that concert's front-of-hall sound and this does it more than adequately. But all that aside, it's just a very fine recording.

I call 1990 and 1991 with Bruce and Vince the Grateful Dead's "Orchestral" years. The sound is always homogenous all the way through, and although Jerry doesn't boggle the mind with supercharged gnat notes, the band has a cohesive ensemble sound and I like it very much. 

With Bruce and Vince, Phil just playing low end and Bobby improvising adroitly, there was exhibited a polished sound in those years that still had a fair amount of the band's pop. Jerry finally had a chance to hang back and let the others supply the elements he always had to supply when the band was somewhat frequency challenged in the earlier days. Besides, he'd grown up and didn't need to be running off willy - nilly seeking a rock and roll flame to fix his waxing fire. This is much more front porch Jerry.

What is also evident was that Bruce and Vince did not emulate Bobby's playing (like Brent had so often in the 80's) which gave Bobby the chance to add complex figures that are absolutely captivating to a guitar loving heart.

Santana joins them on Bird Song but I don't know why, really. I cannot discern his addition to the mix. This Bird Song kinda gets cooking but just doesn't have the same pizzazz as I have heard before in too many other versions of this great first end closer.

Foolish Heart as the second set opener is much stronger in scope and pretty well executed as it falls backwards into Saint and it rocks pretty well. 

I gotta say this about Phil: regardless of all the other members of the band then, Phil is just a relentless source of growling pleasure. You have probably read many of my reviews that address this. In 90-91 Phil was outfitted with the "Aural Exciter" and then he stopped using it. In my opinion he has never sounded as good since. The outboard effects device he used at that time lent a unique articulation to each individual bass guitar note. It is an all-consuming captivation; one my ear never tires of. I wish he still incorporated it into his onstage effects panel. Never in 57 years of listening to rock bass have I ever experienced a bass guitar such as this and to me it is other-wordly.

Crazy Fingers; one of my all-time faves. The ensuing Truckin, Deal and etc are all okay just not barn burners. Drums goes into an interesting space and TOO is always good (even if Healy put a touch of weirdness on Bobby's vocal), but the rest was ho-hum. Wharf>Around>SSDD to complete the previous night's foray into Sugar Mag.

Kudos to Young and the Gem boys. It is excellent sound. The band was just going through its paces and because of that I have to give it only 4 stars. Save for Phil's tractor beam bass lines, there is nothing extraordinary in this show. Even Carlos Santana can't spruce it up more than insert his famous name.
